          0.10319767423613897
        ],
        "order": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Kiran Kedlaya and Lenny Ng",
        "bbox": [
          0.4003759427256493,
          0.1162790700241851,
          0.6071428572206449,
          0.13081395310704425
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_9",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-1 By differentiating Pn(x)/(rk - 1)\"+1 tuting x = 1 yields Pn+1 (1) = -(n + 1)kPn(1). Since Po (1) = 1, an easy induction gives Pn (1) = (-k)\"n! for all n ≥ 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.0939849633458646,
          0.16567460348063626,
          0.4906015053358316,
          0.23875286168697646
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "For i, j = 1,2,3, let Aij denote the position in row i and column j. Without loss of generality, we may assume that Player 1's first move is at Al. Player 0 then plays at A22:",
        "bbox": [
          0.5545112848301682,
          0.16715116268655192,
          0.9191729345463578,
          0.22529069784923753
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_13",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.684210524722984,
          0.23691860472795043,
          0.7500000000888167,
          0.2790697667947895
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note: one can also argue by expanding in Taylor series around 1. Namely, we have",
        "bbox": [
          0.12593985670079827,
          0.24553571446606817,
          0.4906015054724391,
          0.2733134922998525
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.1616541355837244,
          0.28488372123343236,
          0.1710526314745462,
          0.2950581394860443
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_14",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "After Player 1's second move, at least one of A23 and A32 remains vacant. Without loss of generality, assume A23 remains vacant; Player 0 then plays there.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563909812265037,
          0.2950581394060921,
          0.9172932332919881,
          0.3358134920448232
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_0",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.12781954860330563,
          0.32703488360354704,
          0.14473684218616806,
          0.33430232561802936
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0002",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_15",
