    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0004",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_16",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_16",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(a) The 2 x 2 submatrix formed by rows 2 and i and by columns 2 and 3 contains two zeroes and two empty positions.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5676691855585514,
          0.43895348849160554,
          0.9192874974770199,
          0.4811507936552384
        ],
        "order": 14
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_17",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(b) Column j contains one zero and two empty positions.",
        "bbox": [
          0.56766918441853,
          0.4883432541926127,
          0.9210526318721967,
          0.5145348836549228
        ],
        "order": 15
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0005",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_3",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-2 Draw a great circle through two of the points. There are two closed hemispheres with this great circle as boundary, and each of the other three points lies in one of them. By the pigeonhole principle, two of those three points lie in the same hemisphere, and that hemisphere thus contains four of the five given points.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09586466658834576,
          0.5130813952503265,
          0.49060151109241035,
          0.6001727216743367
        ],
        "order": 16
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0006",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_18",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Player 0 next plays at Ajj. To prevent a zero column, Player 1 must play in column j, upon which Player 0 completes the 2 x 2 submatrix in (a) for the win.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563452007123172,
          0.527529761791416,
          0.9210526389119592,
          0.5689412545068072
        ],
        "order": 17
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note: one can also solve this problem directly by making a tree of possible play sequences. This tree can be considerably collapsed using symmetries: the symmetry between rows and columns, the invariance of the outcome under reordering of rows or columns, and the fact that the scenario after a sequence of moves does not depend on the order of the moves (sometimes called \"transposition invariance\").",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563909686616625,
          0.5755813957052107,
          0.9193399577635051,
          0.6889880951347501
        ],
        "order": 18
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0007",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_4",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note: by a similar argument, one can prove that among any n + 3 points on an n-dimensional sphere, some n + 2 of them lie on a closed hemisphere. (One cannot get by with only n + 2 points: put them at the vertices of a regular simplex.) Namely, any n of the points lie on a great sphere, which forms the boundary of two hemispheres; of the remaining three points, some two lie in the same hemisphere.",
        "bbox": [
          0.127426727581664,
          0.6061046518098618,
          0.49060151260400175,
          0.7200133062145303
        ],
        "order": 19
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0008",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_20",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note (due to Paul Cheng): one can reduce Determinant Tic-Tac-Toe to a variant of ordinary tic-tac-toe. Namely, consider a tic-tac-toe grid labeled as follows:",
        "bbox": [
          0.558270678428266,
          0.6961805555560558,
          0.9210526389119592,
          0.7383720928122313
        ],
        "order": 20
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0009",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_5",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_5",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-3 Note that each of the sets {1}, {2},..., {n) has the desired property. Moreover, for each set S with integer average m that does not contain m, SU{m} also has average m, while for each set T of more than one element with integer average m that contains m, T \\ {m} also has average m. Thus the subsets other than {1}, 12},.., In} can be grouped in pairs, so In — n is even.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09586466658834576,
          0.7311046510642799,
          0.4907202141283578,
          0.8444767439484643
        ],
        "order": 21
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0010",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_21",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_21",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.6691393292555204,
          0.7513200873200352,
          0.7650711989778207,
          0.8023313489792574
        ],
        "order": 22
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_22",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Then each term in the expansion of the determinant occurs in a row or column of the grid. Suppose Player 1 first plays in the top left. Player 0 wins by playing first in the top row, and second in the left column. Then there are only one row and column left for Player 1 to threaten, and Player 1 cannot already threaten both on the third move, so Player 0 has time to block both.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563909722252589,
          0.815406976737519,
          0.9210526404235507,
          0.9142441860723478
        ],
        "order": 23
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0011",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_6",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_001_6",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-4 (partly due to David Savitt) Player 0 wins with optimal play. In fact, we prove that Player 1 cannot prevent Player 0 from creating a row of all zeroes, a column of all zeroes, or a 2 x 2 submatrix of all zeroes. Each of these forces the determinant of the matrix to be zero.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09586466658834576,
          0.8575581394000359,
          0.4906015093066961,
          0.9273313491533443
        ],
        "order": 24
      }
    ]
  }
